    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-11T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-11T12:00:00-05:00" n="411"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d411">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890G.24/38: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-11T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 11, 1942—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 11—3:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4483. We took up with the Foreign Office the question set forth in the
                    Department’s telegram No. 3381, July 21, 12 p.m.,<note n="16" xml:id="d411fn16"
                        >See footnote 14, above.</note> and have now received from the Foreign
                    Office an assurance that the British Ambassador at Baghdad has been instructed
                    to consult with our Chargé d’Affaires “and to endeavor to assist him in reaching
                    an agreed solution with the Iraqi Government”.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Baghdad.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
